SIMPLE: hemlock
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hemlock
<hw>Hem"lock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hemeluc</ets>, <ets>humloc</ets>, AS. <ets>hemlic</ets>,
<ets>hymlic</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The name of
several poisonous umbelliferous herbs having finely cut leaves and small
white flowers, as the <spn>Cicuta maculata</spn>, <spn>Cicuta
bulbifera</spn>, and <spn>Cicuta virosa</spn>, and the <spn>Conium
maculatum</spn>. See <er>Conium</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The potion of <xex>hemlock</xex> administered to
Socrates is by some thought to have been a decoction of <spn>Cicuta
virosa</spn>, or <xex>water hemlock</xex>, by others, of <spn>Conium
maculatum</spn>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>An evergreen tree common in North
America (<spn>Abies Canadensis</spn> <it>or</it> <spn>Tsuga
Canadensis</spn>); hemlock spruce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The murmuring pines and the <qex>hemlocks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The wood or timber of the hemlock tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Ground hemlock</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Dwarf
hemlock</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Ground</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hemmel</ent>⟦br⟧
